{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The critical role HRM can play in making AI-usage more human-centric is first by providing training and development opportunities to decision-makers in the organization on how AI works and how to use AI in a way that benefits employee and organizational outcomes (e.g., Arslan et al., 2022; Malik et al., 2022).",
    "Second, to address the issues of trust in AI, HRM professionals can play a more active role in addressing concerns about job transformation (Huang et al., 2019), professional identity (e.g., Mirbabaie et al., 2022), AI training (Chowdhury et al., 2023a), and have employees be part of the AI implementation decisionmaking (e.g., Bankins, 2021; Bankins et al., 2022).",
    "Alleviating fears and concerns of employees is critical for AI implementation to succeed in the workplace and to identify more effective ways to implement AI in later stages (e.g., Park et al., 2021).",
    "Each of these concerns also affects organizational culture.",
    "As more and more machines enter the workforce, replacing human beings, questions are emerging on the changing cultural dynamics within firms (Frangos, 2022; RoŽman et al., 2022; Chowdhury et al., 2023a)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
